.TH "Element.scroll_event" "JS" "April 7, 2023" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Element.scroll_event \- Element: scroll event
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]scroll\f[B]\f[R] event fires when an element has been
scrolled.
To detect when scrolling has completed, see the
\f[CR]Element: scrollend event\f[R].
.SH SYNTAX
Use the event name in methods like \f[CR]addEventListener()\f[R], or set
an event handler property.
.IP
.EX
addEventListener(\[dq]scroll\[dq], (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {});

onscroll = (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {};
.EE
.SH EVENT TYPE
A generic \f[CR]Event\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
The following examples show how to use the \f[CR]scroll\f[R] event with
an event listener and with the \f[CR]onscroll\f[R] event handler
property.
The \f[CR]setTimeout()\f[R] method is used to throttle the event handler
because \f[CR]scroll\f[R] events can fire at a high rate.
For additional examples that use \f[CR]requestAnimationFrame()\f[R], see
the \f[CR]Document: scroll event\f[R] page.
.SS Using \f[CR]scroll\f[R] with an event listener
The following example shows how to use the \f[CR]scroll\f[R] event to
detect when the user is scrolling inside an element:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]div\f[R]
  id=\[dq]scroll\-box\[dq]
  style=\[dq]overflow: scroll; height: 100px; width: 100px; float: left;\[dq]>
  <\f[B]p\f[R] style=\[dq]height: 200px; width: 200px;\[dq]>Scroll me!</\f[B]p\f[R]>
</\f[B]div\f[R]>
<\f[B]p\f[R] style=\[dq]text\-align: center;\[dq] id=\[dq]output\[dq]>Waiting on scroll events...</\f[B]p\f[R]>
.EE
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] element = document.querySelector(\[dq]div#scroll\-box\[dq]);
\f[B]const\f[R] output = document.querySelector(\[dq]p#output\[dq]);

element.addEventListener(\[dq]scroll\[dq], (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  output.innerHTML = \[dq]Scroll event fired!\[dq];
  setTimeout(() \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    output.innerHTML = \[dq]Waiting on scroll events...\[dq];
  }, 1000);
});
.EE
.SS Using \f[CR]onscroll\f[R] event handler property
The following example shows how to use the \f[CR]onscroll\f[R] event
handler property to detect when the user is scrolling:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]div\f[R]
  id=\[dq]scroll\-box\[dq]
  style=\[dq]overflow: scroll; height: 100px; width: 100px; float: left;\[dq]>
  <\f[B]p\f[R] style=\[dq]height: 200px; width: 200px;\[dq]>Scroll me!</\f[B]p\f[R]>
</\f[B]div\f[R]>
<\f[B]p\f[R] id=\[dq]output\[dq] style=\[dq]text\-align: center;\[dq]>Waiting on scroll events...</\f[B]p\f[R]>
.EE
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] element = document.querySelector(\[dq]div#scroll\-box\[dq]);
\f[B]const\f[R] output = document.querySelector(\[dq]p#output\[dq]);

element.onscroll = (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  output.innerHTML = \[dq]Element scroll event fired!\[dq];
  setTimeout(() \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    output.innerHTML = \[dq]Waiting on scroll events...\[dq];
  }, 1000);
};
.EE
